50|$|In 1833, E. J. Dent (maker of the Great Clock of the Houses of Parliament) {{experimented with}} a glass balance spring. This was much less {{affected}} by heat than steel, reducing the compensation required, and also didn't rust. Other trials with glass springs revealed that they were difficult and expensive to make, and they suffered from a widespread perception of fragility, which persisted until the time of fibreglass and <b>fibre-optic</b> <b>materials.</b>|$|E

